#!/usr/bin/env python3
# LEGACY RECOVERY VERB (design/FABLE-BOUNDARY-MULTIPLEX-AND-CLI-REBASE-SPEC.md §5, ratified row 1631): the direct-psql original of ./distance-to-clean, kept whole and executable for operator recovery when the boundary is down -- ./distance-to-clean itself is now the SERVICED path (a boundary_cli_client.py HTTP client); this file's own capability is unchanged, just demoted by placement, never deleted.
"""distance-to-clean — the composed closure-debt verb (BACKLOG "Five-item batch,
maintainer-approved 2026-07-11 evening", item 1; vestigial_documentation/design/ORCH-RETROSPECTIVE-RUN10.md Finding 1).

WHAT THIS IS FOR, VERBATIM FROM THE MAINTAINER'S CONDITION: "we shouldn't aggregate
something ... that may have valid use-cases disaggregated (indeed, it is my sense that the
disaggregated view ... is the default). If that can work simultaneously, I'd concur." So:
`led review-gap`, `led question-status`, and `led work violations` are UNTOUCHED by this file
and remain the documented default, disaggregated way to read closure debt. This verb is
strictly ADDITIVE — it reads the SAME EXISTING VIEWS those commands (and the stop-gate hook)
already read (`review_gap`, `question_status`, `work_item_violations`, `work_item_current`,
`work_review_gap`) and prints their counts and ids in ONE pass, computing nothing new: no new
SQL logic, no new join, no derived predicate beyond what those views already compute. It
exists to kill the run10 pattern the retrospective named: 47 of run10's 299 invocations (about
16%) were bare polls of `./led review-gap` alone, because one call could not answer "how far am
I from a clean stop" — this call can.

PARITY WITH THE STOP-GATE (dtc-stopgate-parity, defect fix 2026-07-16): this tool's job is to
answer, ahead of time, the same question `hooks/stop_clean_exit.py::_collect_debt()` (the
actual stop-gate) answers at Stop-hook time. That function checks FIVE categories, not three
— `review_gap`, `question_status`, `work_item_violations`, PLUS `work_item_current` (open work
items claimed and undischarged) and `work_review_gap` (deferred-review obligations opened by
`--review-deferred` closes). The first three were mirrored here from the start; the WORK-ITEMS
and WORK-REVIEW-GAP sections below close the remaining gap — a world could previously read
"TOTAL debt: 0" here and still have the stop-gate block on open claimed work or a deferred
review. WORK-ITEMS carries one honest difference from the hook, not a shortcut: the hook
narrows blocking work items to ones claimed by THIS session (`stamp_session` matching the
Stop-hook's own `session_id`, read off the hook's stdin payload) unless a claim is bequeathed.
This tool is invoked directly by the operator, off no such payload — it has no session identity
to narrow with, ever. Rather than silently under-report, it reproduces exactly the DEGRADE
branch `_collect_debt()` itself falls back to whenever session ownership can't be proven (its
own "NAMED CHOICE -- STOP-GATE QUEUE SEMANTICS" docstring section): every open, claimed item
counts as debt, regardless of claimant, and the printed line says so explicitly rather than
leaving the gap silent.

WHY A NEW VERB, NOT A `led` SUBCOMMAND: `bootstrap/templates/led.tmpl` is a live-executed
template (the "live verbs" ruling, 2026-07-11 — every scaffolded world's `./led` shim `exec`s
this file directly, every invocation) and is therefore freeze-bound: it may only be edited
while no wired session is live anywhere. A brand-new template file carries no such constraint
(a file nothing yet execs is safe to add at any time), and mirrors this project's own existing
precedent for growing the verb surface without touching an existing live verb: `audit.tmpl`
landed as a fifth verb alongside led/judge/pickup exactly this way (BACKLOG "Contemporaneity
indictment"). `bootstrap/new-project.sh`'s shim-writing loop is extended by one name
(`distance-to-clean`) to wire it in — that script is not itself live-executed by any running
world (only the scaffold-time act reads it), so widening its verb list carries none of
led.tmpl's freeze risk.

Sections emitted, one call, one pass:
  REVIEW-GAP        — `review_gap` (the SAME view `led review-gap` reads): every row (id) an
                      obliged actor wrote with no distinct-actor attest countersign yet.
  QUESTION-STATUS   — `question_status` (the SAME view `led question-status` reads): every
                      open (unanswered) question, by id — the view's own pre-computed
                      `answered` column is READ, not re-derived.
  WORK-VIOLATIONS   — `work_item_violations` (the SAME view `led work violations` reads): every
                      violation row, by slug — UNAVAILABLE (not zero) on a world whose kernel
                      predates kernel/lineage/s22-work-item-ledger.sql, mirroring pickup.tmpl's
                      own honest IN-FLIGHT fallback for the identical capability gap.
  WORK-ITEMS        — added 2026-07-16 (dtc-stopgate-parity defect fix). `work_item_current`
                      (the SAME view the stop-gate hook reads): every OPEN, CLAIMED work item,
                      by slug — the stop-gate's own DEGRADE predicate (see module docstring
                      PARITY section above), since this tool has no session identity to narrow
                      claims to "claimed by THIS session" the way the hook can. The printed
                      line names this explicitly so the caveat is never silent. UNAVAILABLE
                      (not zero) on a pre-s22 world, same posture as WORK-VIOLATIONS above.
  WORK-REVIEW-GAP   — added 2026-07-16 (dtc-stopgate-parity defect fix). `work_review_gap`
                      (the SAME view the stop-gate hook reads): every work item closed with
                      `--review-deferred` that has no distinct-actor attest yet, by slug —
                      UNAVAILABLE (not zero) on a world whose kernel predates the s29
                      work-review-gap view, same posture as WORK-VIOLATIONS above.
  DOC-ATTESTATION   — added 2026-07-12 (tracker item `abc-loop-offering`; design/
                      ORCH-SPEC-ABC-OFFERING.md Stage C). Counts every in-scope `*.md` under
                      this deployment whose ADR-0017 A:B:C fresh-context attestation is STALE
                      or NO-ATTESTATION (never ATTESTED — see `./attest-doc check`, this
                      deployment's own verb, for the per-document classification this section
                      reads via the SAME `gates/doc_attestation_presence.py` classify()
                      autoharn's own checkout owns — ADR-0012 P1, one classifier, two callers).
                      NOT counted by default: this section is gated OFF unless
                      `mechanisms.doc_attestation.mode` is `"observe"` in this deployment's
                      `.claude/apparatus.json` (missing file/key/mechanism resolves to `"off"`,
                      never widens on a bad value — the SAME never-widens posture every other
                      mechanism in this project's apparatus switchboard already has). OFF is
                      not a cost decision (this section, like `./attest-doc check`, is pure
                      hashing — no LLM call, no network) — it is an ADOPTION decision: a
                      deployment that has not adopted the A:B:C loop as a workflow should not
                      see debt for a discipline it never opted into (design/
                      ORCH-SPEC-ABC-OFFERING.md §4).
  TOTAL             — the sum of the counts above (REVIEW-GAP + QUESTION-STATUS +
                      WORK-VIOLATIONS + WORK-ITEMS + WORK-REVIEW-GAP, plus DOC-ATTESTATION when
                      its mode is not `"off"`; 0 iff every counted dimension is individually
                      clean) plus the one-line verdict `led review-gap`/`question-status`/
                      `work violations`/`attest-doc check` would each print separately today,
                      now in one place.

Deployment resolution, connection posture, and path resolution: byte-identical to
pickup.tmpl's own module docstring section of the same name — this file executes IN PLACE out
of the autoharn checkout (the "live verbs" ruling), `PICKUP_DEPLOYMENT` is set by the
scaffolded shim to the world's own `deployment.json`, `AUTOHARN` resolves from this file's own
on-disk path (overridable), and every query here queries under the project's OWN granted role
(`SET ROLE <dep.role>`) — the same "what can the OPERATING AGENT see" posture pickup.tmpl's
REVIEW-DEBT section already documents, reused rather than re-derived (ADR-0012 P1: one
resolution mechanism, not a second copy).

Read-only throughout: every query here is a SELECT; this script issues no INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE.
Lazy imports banned (top-of-file only, per this project's inherited convention).
"""
from __future__ import annotations

